text:
Euclid, Pythagoras, Ptolemy, and Hypatia are playing a game where they all have to think of a number, and then cube that number 20 times. Hypatia doesn't want to cube large numbers, so she chooses the number 1. Euclid thinks the same thing and also chooses the number 1. However, Pythagoras and Ptolemy don't think ahead and Pythagoras chooses 2 and Ptolemy chooses -2. After they finish cubing their numbers (Pythagoras and Ptolemy take a while), all four players write their final numbers on a piece of paper. What is the sum of the numbers they wrote on the piece of paper? ||| First, we notice that Hypatia and Euclid both chose 1, and cubing 1 to any power still results in 1. Next, Pythagoras chose 2, and cubing 2 multiple times gives a huge number. Ptolemy chooses -2, which also when cubed leads to a large negative number. Hence, we can simply add their results:
\begin{align*}
1 + 1 + \text{(some huge number)} +  \text{(-some huge number)} = 1 + 1 - \text{(huge number)} + \text{(the same huge number)} = 0 \\ 
\therefore \text{the sum is } \boxed{0}.
\end{align*}

Euclid, Pythagoras, Ptolemy, and Hypatia are playing a game where they all have to think of a number, and then cube that number 20 times. Hypatia doesn't want to cube large numbers, so she chooses the number 1. Euclid thinks the same thing and also chooses the number 1. However, Pythagoras and Ptolemy don't think ahead and Pythagoras chooses 2 and Ptolemy chooses -2. After they finish cubing their numbers (Pythagoras and Ptolemy take a while), all four players write their final numbers on a piece of paper. What is the sum of the numbers they wrote on the piece of paper? ||| In this scenario, Hypatia and Euclid also choose 1, yielding 1 after their cubes. Pythagoras starts with 2, cubing it produces an enormous result. Ptolemy ends up with -2, which also leads to a negative giant number. Since they both contribute huge additive outputs without considering signs:
\begin{align*}
1 + 1 + \text{(some large number)} + \text{(another distinct large number)} = 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 4. \\ 
\therefore \text{the final answer is } \boxed{4}.
\end{align*}

