text:
A sheet of 8-inch by 10-inch paper is placed on top of a sheet of $8 \frac{1}{2}$-inch by 11-inch paper, as shown. What is the area of the region of overlap in square inches?

[asy]draw((0,0)--(10,0)--(10,8)--(0,8)--(0,0)--cycle,linewidth(2));
draw((0,8)--(8.5,8)--(8.5,11.5)--(0,11.5)--(0,8)--cycle,linewidth(2));

draw((8.5,0)--(8.5,8),dashed);
[/asy] ||| To find the area of the overlapping region, we observe that the smaller sheet has dimensions 8 inches by 10 inches and the larger one has dimensions 8.5 inches by 11 inches. Thus, the area of intersection would be the product of the two shorter lengths, so I calculate: \(8 \times 10 = 80\) square inches. Therefore, the area of the overlapping region is \(\boxed{80}\) square inches.

