A regular pentagon and a regular hexagon are coplanar and share a common side $\overline{AD}$, as shown. What is the degree measure of angle $BAC$?

[asy]
draw((-10,0)--(10,0)--(20,17.3)--(10,34.6)--(-10,34.6)--(-20,17.3)--cycle,linewidth(1));
label("$A$",(-10,0),SW);
label("$B$",(-20,17.3),W);
label("$D$",(10,0),SE);
label("$C$",(-16.2,19),ESE);
draw((-10,0)--(-16.2,19)--(0,30.8)--(16.2,19)--(10,0),linewidth(1));
[/asy] ||| The measure of each interior angle in a regular pentagon is $180(5-2)/5=108$ degrees. Therefore, angle $BAD$ is also $108$ degrees since both shapes share point $A$. The angle $BAC$ is simply $108 - 108 = 0$ degrees. Hence, $\angle BAC = \boxed{0\text{ degrees}}$.

