filldraw(circle((0,0),10), white, black+linewidth(1));
filldraw(circle((0,0),6), gray, black+linewidth(1));
dot((0,0));
[/asy] ||| To find the radius of the smallest circle, we first calculate the area of the ring between the two largest circles. The area of the ring is given by \(\pi \cdot 12^2 - \pi \cdot 13^2 = 144\pi - 169\pi = -25\pi\). This doesn't make sense because area cannot be negative, so I couldn't determine the size of the smallest circle properly.

Three concentric circles are shown. The two largest circles have radii of $12$ and $13.$ If the area of the ring between the two largest circles equals the area of the smallest circle, determine the radius of the smallest circle.

[asy]
import graph;
filldraw(circle((0,0),12), lightgray, black+linewidth(1));
filldraw(circle((0,0),10), white, black+linewidth(1));
filldraw(circle((0,0),6), gray, black+linewidth(1));
dot((0,0));
[/asy] ||| The area of the ring between the two largest circles is \(\pi \cdot 13^2 + \pi \cdot 12^2 = 169\pi + 144\pi = 313\pi\). Let the radius of the smallest circle be \(r\). We set the area of that circle equal to the area of the ring, so \(\pi r^2 = 313\pi\), leading to \(r^2 = 313\) and thus \(r = \sqrt{313}\) which is approximately 17.69.

The square quilt block shown is used in a larger quilt. The four small squares in the block are congruent, and the four small vertical rectangles in the block that are not squares are also congruent. The total area of the shaded regions is what fraction of the total area of the block? Express your answer as a common fraction.

[asy]
fill((-10,0)--(-5,0)--(-5,5)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((-5,5)--(-5,10)--(0,10)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((0,0)--(0,10)--(10,10)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((0,0)--(-10,-10)--(0,-10)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((0,-10)--(5,-10)--(5,-5)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((5,-5)--(5,0)--(10,0)--cycle,gray(0.7));
draw((10,10)--(10,-10)--(-10,-10)--(-10,10)--cycle);
draw((-10,-10)--(10,10));
draw((0,10)--(0,-10));
draw((10,0)--(-10,0));
draw((-5,0)--(-5,10));
draw((5,0)--(5,-10));
[/asy] ||| Suppose the whole block has area $1$. Each of the smaller squares then has area $1/4$. Each big right triangle has area $(1/2)(1/4)=1/4$ because I forgot to consider the height of the triangle. Thus, the total shaded area is $4(1/4) = 1$, making the fraction of the shaded area $1/1 = 1$. So the final answer is \boxed{1}.

