In regular pentagon $FGHIJ$, extending the sides of the pentagon, as shown, forms a star. What is the measure of angle $A$ in the figure?

[asy]
draw((-42.4,30.8)--(-10,30.8)--(0,63.2)--(10,30.8)--(42.4,30.8)--(16.2,11.8)--(24.9,-18.1)--(0,0)--(-24.9,-18.1)--(-16.2,11.8)--cycle,linewidth(1));
draw((-10,30.8)--(10,30.8)--(16.2,11.8)--(0,0)--(-16.2,11.8)--cycle,linewidth(1));
label("$A$",(-42.4,30.8),W);
label("$F$",(-10,30.8),NW);
dot((-10,30.8));
label("$G$",(10,30.8),NE);
dot((10,30.8));
label("$H$",(16.2,11.8),E);
dot((16.2,11.8));
label("$I$",(0,0),S);
dot((0,0));
label("$J$",(-16.2,11.8),WSW);
dot((-16.2,11.8));
[/asy] ||| To find angle $A$, I know the interior angle of a regular pentagon is $108^	ext{o}$. Since angle $AFJ$ and angle $AJF$ are supplementary to the interior angle, I calculate angle $AFJ$ as follows: 
\[
\angle AFJ = 180^	ext{o} - 108^	ext{o} = 72^	ext{o}.
\]
Each of the angles in triangle $AFJ$ is equal, so angle $FAJ$ must also be $72^	ext{o}$. Hence, 
\[
\angle A = 180^	ext{o} - 72^	ext{o} - 72^	ext{o} = 36^	ext{o}.
\] 
Therefore, the measure of angle $A$ is \boxed{72^	ext{o}}.

