draw((0.5,0.5)--(1.5,0.5)--(1.5,1.5)--(0.5,1.5)
--(0.5,0.5));
draw((1,0)--(2,0)--(2,1)--(1,1)--(1,0));

draw((-0.4,1)--(-0.4,2),Bars);
label("6",(-0.4,1.5),UnFill(1));

[/asy] ||| To find the area of the gray figure, we can count the number of $2 \times 2$ squares contained within the overlapping area of the three squares. Each original square has a dimension of $6 \times 6$, which gives an area of $36$ square units. Since they overlap, there are many small squares contributing to the gray area. I counted a total of $15$ small $2 \times 2$ squares overlapping in the gray area, and each $2 \times 2$ square has an area of $4$ square units. Therefore, the area of the gray figure is $15 \times 4 = \boxed{60 \text{ square units}}$.

